<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-724-998  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 724 998.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  Oct 2 1989 n437 p3(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM surprises with bleak forecast. (revenue for 1989disappointing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sperling, Ed; Terdoslavich, William.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM may not have a strong financial year, despite an earlierprediction of solid sales to last through the end of 1989.andP;  Theoptimistic forecast, reported on Sep 18, 1989, was based on thestrength of the US dollar overseas, the transition to new productsand increased leasing of IBM products in the US.andP;  Actually, thecompany is beginning cost-cutting measures to increase revenue andcut expenses, beginning with the research and developmentdepartment.andP;  Projects that will not produce revenue in the shortrun will be reduced.andP;  Financial analysts on Wall Street areimpatient for IBM to recover: the company had earnings of $10.77per share in 1984, and has not come close to that figure sincethen.andP;  Many on Wall Street believe that IBM has lost somecredibility with the financial industry because it changed itsfinancial outlook only nine days after expressing optimism.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (finance).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Financial ReportForecastingRevenueCost ReductionWall StreetProfit.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>